{"title_page": "Tom McCarthy (novelist)", "text_new": "{{redirect-distinguish|Men in Space|Man in Space|Men into Space|Manned spaceflight|Spaceman (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=October 2015}}\n{{External links|date=October 2015}}}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Tom McCarthy\n| image =\n| imagesize = 60\n| caption = Tom McCarthy\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1969}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| occupation = Novelist, writer, artist\n| nationality = British\n| period = 2002\u2013present\n| genre =\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'', ''Men in Space'', ''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'', [[C (novel)|''C'']], ''[[Satin Island]]''\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| website = {{url|http://vargas.org.uk/publications/ins/index.html}}\n}}\n'''Tom McCarthy''' (born 1969) is an English writer and artist. He has written four novels, his [[debut novel]] ''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'' published in 2005 by [[Metronome (artists' and writers' organ)|Metronome]] and his most recent published novel, ''[[Satin Island]]'', in 2015 by [[Alfred A. Knopf]].\n\n==Life and work==\nTom McCarthy was born in London in 1969 and lives in [[Central London]]. McCarthy grew up in [[Greenwich]], south London and was educated at [[Dulwich College]] (1978 to 1986) and later [[New College, Oxford]], where he studied English literature. He lived in Prague, where he worked as a nude model and in an American bar; Berlin, where he worked in an Irish pub; and Amsterdam, where he worked in a restaurant kitchen and reviewed books for the local edition of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine<ref name=\"thedaysofyore.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedaysofyore.com/tom-mccarthy/ |title=Tom McCarthy |publisher=The Days of Yore |date=2011-06-20 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> in the early 90s, before moving back to London. McCarthy's time in Prague forms the basis for his novel ''Men in Space''.<ref Name=\"Independent\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html \"Tom McCarthy: How he became one of the brightest new prospects in British fiction\" ''The Independent\" 21 September 2007]</ref> McCarthy has also worked as a television script editor, and co-edited ''[[Mute Magazine|Mute]]'' magazine. Prior to his success he lived and wrote in a tower block flat on the [[Golden Lane Estate]] beside [[Barbican Estate|the Barbican]].<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\n===Writing and publishing===\nMcCarthy's debut novel ''Remainder'' was written in 2001<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|last=Robson |first=Leo |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2010/08/mccarthy-novel-serge-smith |title=C |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=2010-08-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> and rejected by mainstream UK publishers. It was published in November 2005 by the small Paris-based art publisher [[Metronome Press]] and distributed through gallery and museum shops, but not in chain bookstores<ref Name=\"Independent\"/> and then received widespread critical attention in the literary and mainstream press, with one of its first reviews, in December 2005, on ReadySteadyBook who called it \"one of the most important novels written in a long, long time.\" The ''London Review of Books'' called it \"a very good novel indeed\" and ''The Independent'' claimed that \"its minatory brilliance calls for classic status\".<ref>{{cite web|author=the complete review \u2013 all rights reserved |url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/gbx/mccarthy.htm |title=Remainder \u2013 Tom McCarthy |publisher=Complete-review.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> The novel was re-published by the independent publisher [[Alma Books]] in the UK (2006), and the [[Bertelsmann]] subsidiary [[Vintage Books|Vintage]] in the US (2007), where it ranked as an Amazon top one-hundred seller and entered the ''Los Angeles Times'' Bestseller list.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} On its American publication the ''New York Times'' dedicated the front cover of its book section to the novel, calling the book \"a work of novelistic philosophy, as disturbing as it is funny\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/25/books/review/Schillinger.t.html | work=The New York Times | title=Play It Again | first=Liesl | last=Schillinger | date=25 February 2007}}</ref> In 2008 ''Remainder'' won the fourth annual [[Believer Book Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/200806/?read=believer_book_award |title=The Believer \u2013 The Believer Book Award |publisher=Believermag.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Zadie Smith wrote in the ''New York Review of Books'' that it was \"one of the great English novels of the last ten years\", suggesting it showed a future path that the novel \"might, with difficulty, follow\".<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Zadie Smith |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22083 |title=Two Paths for the Novel &#124; The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=20 November 2008 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> It has since been translated into fourteen languages, and a film adaptation directed by [[Omer Fast]] was released in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/novel-idea/ |title=Frieze Magazine &#124; Archive &#124; Novel Idea |publisher=Frieze.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1847672/|title=Remainder (2015)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref>Editions have been published, or are scheduled to be published, in Chinese (Shanghai Translation Publishing House and Ten Points Publishing House), Croatian ([http://oceanmore.hr/knjiga.php?id_knjiga=47 Oceanmore]), Dutch ([http://uitgeverijprometheus.nl/index.php?option=com_pac&view=boek_detail&isbn=9789044614152&Itemid=6 Prometheus]), French (Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures and [http://www.jailu.com/albums_detail.cfm?id=34922 J\u2019ai Lu]), German ([http://www.diaphanes.de/scripts/buch.php?ID=172 Diaphanes]), Greek (Papyros Publishing Group), Hebrew (Achuzat Bayit), Italian ([http://isbnedizioni.it/catalogo/narrativa/deja-vu/ ISBN Edizioni]), Japanese (Shinchosha Publishing Company), Korean (Minumsa), Portuguese ([http://www.estampa.pt/novosite/index.php?t=detalhe&id=1792 Editorial Estampa]), Russian ([http://admarginem.ru/books/1884/ Ad Marginem]), Spanish ([http://www.lenguadetrapo.com/libro.php?sec=OL&item=229 Lengua de Trapo]) and Turkish (Encore Yay\u0131nlar\u0131).</ref> Several big publishing houses who had rejected the novel returned to him with enthusiastic offers, which McCarthy rejected, commenting that \"it's the same book as it was two years ago.\"<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\n{{anchor|Tintin and the Secret of Literature}}\nA work of literary criticism by McCarthy, ''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'', was released by [[Granta Books]] in June 2006, with French (Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures), Spanish (El Tercer Nombre), Italian (Piemme) and American editions (Counterpoint) following in 2007-8.<ref>Tom McCarthy, ''Tintin e il segreto della letteratura'' (Milan: Piemme, 2007). {{ISBN|978-88-384-8668-5}}; ''Tintin et le secret de la litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris: Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures, 2006). {{ISBN|978-2-01-237258-0}}; ''Tint\u00edn y el secreto de la literatura'' (Madrid: El Tercer Nombre, 2007). {{ISBN|978-84-96693-11-1}}</ref> The book attempted a reading of Herg\u00e9's ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' books through the prism of structuralist and post-structuralist literary theory. It divided reviewers, with some critics disliking the book's references to [[Jacques Derrida]] and [[Roland Barthes]]. Killian Fox in ''The Observer'' praised \"its author's obsessive approach, his breathtaking grasp of the oeuvre and the sheer exuberance with which he tackles his subject\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Killian Fox |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jul/16/booksforchildrenandteenagers.features |title=Observer review: Tintin and the Secret of Literature by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Guardian |date= 16 July 2006|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> However, in ''The Guardian'', Kathryn Hughes criticised its methodology and style: \"McCarthy's text has that pleased-with-itself smirk that was so characteristic of the early 90s, when journalists started purloining critical theory from the academy, liking the way it made them feel clever\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Kathryn Hughes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jul/15/highereducation.news |title=Review: Tintin and the Secret of Literature by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books |publisher=The Guardian |date= 14 July 2006|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> McCarthy commented: \"Granta asked if I wanted to write a book on Freud or Derrida or someone like that, and I said: 'Well, if I write about Herg\u00e9 I can write about Freud, Derrida and whole bunch of other people, plus it'll be much more fun.' It was received well for the most part. There were one or two hilarious English reviews in which you could virtually see the reviewer's veins bursting with little-England rage at the book's continental bent.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewfromheremagazine.com/2008/03/mike-interviews-tom-mccarthy.html |title=The view from here literary magazine: Mike Interviews: Tom McCarthy Part 1 of 3 |publisher=Viewfromheremagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Alma Books published his second novel, ''Men in Space'', much of which was written prior to ''Remainder''. It has since been published in many languages including Greek and French.<ref>Tom McCarthy, ''Men in space'' (''\u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1'') (Athens: Papyros, 2008). {{ISBN|978-960-6715-60-0}}; ''Les Cosmonautes au paradis'' (Paris: Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures, 2009). {{ISBN|978-2-01-237406-5}}</ref> McCarthy has also published numerous stories, essays and articles on literature, philosophy and art in publications including ''The Observer'', ''The Times Literary Supplement'', ''The London Review of Books'', ''Artforum'' and ''The New York Times'', as well as in anthologies such as ''London from Punk to Blair'' (Reaktion Books), ''Theology and the Political'' (Duke University Press), ''The Milgram Reenactment'' (Jan van Eyck Press) and ''The Empty Page: Fiction Inspired by Sonic Youth'' (Serpent's Tail).\n\nIn 2004 he published an essay on excrement in the work of James Joyce in the online literary journal ''Hypermedia Joyce Studies''. In 2008 an essay by McCarthy on Alain Robbe-Grillet, an author he has often expressed an admiration for, was published in the new Oneworld Classics English edition of Robbe-Grillet's ''Jealousy''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/may/08/top10s.modernists |title=Tom McCarthy's top 10 European modernists &#124; Books &#124; guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian |date= 22 July 2008|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In February 2015 McCarthy published a new novel titled ''Satin Island'' which was shortlisted for that year's [[Man Booker Prize]]; when he began it, he said, \"It's going to have a leitmotif of a parachutist falling to earth, having realised that his parachute has been sabotaged: his relation to the landscape, death, technology.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Johncock|first=Ben|title=Tom McCarthy: My desktop|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/nov/24/tom-mccarthy-desktop|accessdate=17 June 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===McCarthy's International Necronautical Society (INS) and Art===\nSince 1999 McCarthy has been 'general secretary' of a 'semi-fictitious organisation' he co-founded with his friend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblioklept.org/tag/simon-critchley/ |title=Simon Critchley |publisher=Biblioklept |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> the philosopher [[Simon Critchley]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookprizes/8058014/Man-Booker-Prize-the-shortlist.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Man Booker Prize: the shortlist | date=12 October 2010}}</ref> called the International Necronautical Society (INS) \"devoted to mind-bending projects that would do for death what the Surrealists had done for sex\".<ref Name=\"Independent\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/fictionreviews/3667868/Lost-in-the-orbits-of-spies-and-mobsters.html |title=Lost in the orbits of spies and mobsters |publisher=Telegraph |date=13 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Having failed to interest publishers in his novels in 2001-2, he made art projects under the INS name.<ref name=\"thewhitereview.org\">{{cite web|author=Interview with Tom McCarthy |url=http://www.thewhitereview.org/interviews/interview-with-tom-mccarthy-2/ |title=Interview with Tom McCarthy |publisher=The White Review |date=2014-10-31 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref name=\"readysteadybook.com\">{{cite web|author=Anne Sherwood Pundyk |url=http://www.readysteadybook.com/Article.aspx?page=tommccarthy |title=Tom McCarthy \u00ab Interview \u00ab ReadySteadyBook - for literature |publisher=Readysteadybook.com |date=2009-07-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> McCarthy handed out his International Necronautical Society or INS manifestos at a mock art fair organised by artist [[Gavin Turk]].<ref name=\"readysteadybook.com\"/> The INS operates through publications, live events, media interventions and more conventional art exhibitions.\n\nIn a 2007 interview with the website Bookninja, McCarthy explained the circumstances that led to the formation of the INS: \"I was quite well integrated into the art world in London by the late nineties, and on top of that I\u2019d for some time had an interest in the modes and procedures of early twentieth century avant-gardes like the Futurists and Surrealists: their semi-corporate, semi-political structures of committees and subcommittees, their use of manifestos, proclamations and denunciations\".<ref name=\"bookninja1\">{{cite web|url=http://bookninja.com/magazine/fall2007/mccarthy.htm |title=In The Magazine |publisher=Bookninja |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nDespite his initial claim that the INS was 'not an art project',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://surplusmatter.com/interviews/interviews-with/its-impossible-to-think-of-writing-without-thinking-of-death-tom-mccarthy-on-the-necronautical-society/ |title=An Index to the work of Tom McCarthy |publisher=Surplus Matter |date=1 February 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> McCarthy has accepted invitations to show work in his capacity as INS general secretary at art institutions around the world, including Tate Britain and the Institute of Contemporary Art in London, Moderna Museet Stockholm, the Drawing Center New York, Kunstwerke Berlin, Hartware MedienKunstVerein Dortmund, and Substation Gallery Singapore.<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\nThe INS has been described by ''Art Monthly'' as \"a group of wayward literati and sweet-talking parodists\",<ref name=\"necronauts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/art_monthly_04.htm |title=The Necronautical Society \u2013 INS in the Press |publisher=Necronauts.org |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> and as \"obscure\" by ''[[The Australian]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/tintin-and-the-secret-of-literature/story-e6frg8no-1111112339055 | first=Alistair | last=Jones | title=Tintin and the Secret of Literature | date=14 October 2006 | work=The Australian}}</ref> In 2003 the INS hacked the [[BBC]] website and inserted propaganda into its source code. The following year, they set up a broadcasting unit at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]] from which more than forty assistants generated non-stop \"poem-codes\" which were transmitted over FM radio in London and by internet to collaborating radio stations around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almabooks.com/page.html?id=17 |title=Overture Publishing |publisher=Alma Books |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> In 2008 a more mechanical version of this piece was displayed at Stockholm's Moderna Museet, in which an aeroplane Black Box transmitter sent out a stream of similar messages.<ref>{{cite web|author=mikejfrench |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cm4379AkUb0 |title=Tom McCarthy om Black Box |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, after McCarthy and INS Chief Philosopher [[Simon Critchley]] had delivered the 'INS Declaration on Inauthenticity' at New York's Drawing Center, the critic Peter Schwenger alleged in ''[[Triple Canopy (online magazine)|Triple Canopy]]'' that the two men who appeared in the gallery were not in fact Critchley and McCarthy.<ref name=\"canopycanopycanopy1\">{{cite web|url=http://canopycanopycanopy.com/1/state_of_inauthenticity |title=The State of Inauthenticity \u2013 Triple Canopy |publisher=Canopycanopycanopy.com |date=25 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Taking his claim as an inspiration, McCarthy and Critchley did indeed replace themselves with actors when delivering the Declaration one year later at Tate Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/context-comment/video/tate-triennial-2009-prologue-4-borders-simon-critchley-and-tom-mccarthy-tate |title=Tate Channel: Tate Triennial 2009 Prologue 4: Borders |publisher=Tate |date= |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> When invited to deliver the Declaration a third time at the 2009 Athens Biennial, they announced that the Declaration would henceforth be outsourced to any institution who wanted it, and commissioned a Greek translation, which was subsequently delivered by Greek actors in Athens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensbiennial.org/AB2PressReleases&PreviewScheduleENGLISH.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725022238/http://www.athensbiennial.org/AB2PressReleases%26PreviewScheduleENGLISH.pdf |archivedate=25 July 2011 |title=2nd Athens Biennale 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMcCarthy has made independent artworks. In 2005 he exhibited, at The Western Front Gallery, Vancouver, the multimedia installation piece 'Greenwich Degree Zero', produced in collaboration with artist [[Rod Dickinson]], which (in a tribute to [[Joseph Conrad]]'s 1907 novel ''The Secret Agent''), depicted the Greenwich Observatory burning the ground. The piece was subsequently purchased by the Arts Council England's permanent collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/collections/arts-council-collection/greenwich-degree-zero-2005-6/ |title=Greenwich Degree Zero, 2005-6 |publisher=Arts Council |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 he collaborated with French artist Loris Gr\u00e9aud to produce an 'Ontic Helpline' for a fictitious 'Thanatalogical Corporation' \u2013 a black telephone that transfers callers through an endless loop of pre-recorded messages. The telephone was displayed in the FiAC collection in Paris, and purchased by gallerists/collectors Solene Guillier and Nathalie Boutin. McCarthy wrote the script for Johan Grimonprez's feature film ''Double Take'' (2009). The script consists of a short story, loosely based on Borges's '25 August 1983', in which Hitchcock meets his double on the set of one of his films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1386926/ |title=Double Take (2009)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> The film won the Black Pearl award (MEIFF, Abu Dhabi) in 2009. McCarthy has also tutored and lectured at various institutions including the [[Architectural Association]], [[Central Saint Martins School of Art]], the [[Royal College of Art]], [[London Consortium]] and [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Novels==\n===''Remainder''===\n''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'' tells the story of an unnamed hero traumatised by an accident which \"involved something falling from the sky\". Eight and a half million pounds richer due to a compensation settlement but hopelessly estranged from the world around him, ''Remainder'''s protagonist spends his time and money obsessively reconstructing and re-enacting vaguely remembered scenes and situations from his past, such as a large building with piano music in the distance, the familiar smells and sounds of liver frying and spluttering, or lethargic cats lounging on roofs until they tumble off them. These re-enactments are driven by a need to inhabit the world \"authentically\" rather than in the \"second-hand\" manner that his traumatic situation has bequeathed him. When the recreation of mundane events fails to quench this thirst for authenticity, he starts re-enacting more and more violent events.\n\n===''Men in Space''===\nSet in a Central Europe rapidly fragmenting after the fall of Communism, ''Men in Space'' follows a cast of dissolute Bohemians, political refugees, football referees, deaf police agents, assassins and stranded astronauts as they chase a stolen icon painting from Sofia to Prague and beyond. The icon's melancholy orbit is reflected in the various characters' ellipses and near-misses as they career vertiginously through all kinds of space, be it physical, political, emotional or metaphysical. McCarthy uses these settings to present a vision of humanity adrift in history, and a world in a state of disintegration.\n\n===''C''===\nOpening in England at the turn of the twentieth century, ''C'' is the story of a boy named Serge Carrefax, whose father spends his time experimenting with wireless communication while running a school for deaf children. Serge grows up amid the noise and silence with his brilliant but troubled older sister, Sophie: an intense sibling relationship that stays with him as he heads off into an equally troubled larger world. After a fling with a nurse at a Bohemian spa, Serge serves in World War I as a radio operator for reconnaissance planes. When his plane is shot down, Serge is taken to a German prison camp, from which he escapes. Back in London, he's recruited for a mission to Cairo on behalf of the shadowy Empire Wireless Chain.\n\nMcCarthy's novel ''C'' was released in late 2010, in the US with Knopf, in the UK with Jonathan Cape. It divided critics.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/7913342/Peter-Carey-could-be-three-time-Booker-winner.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Stephen | last=Adams | title=Peter Carey could be three-time Booker winner | date=27 July 2010}}</ref>\nMcCarthy has described this novel in previous interviews as dealing with technology and mourning. The book was shortlisted for the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://surplusmatter.com/interviews/interviews-with/watch-that-space-or-literatures-proper-territory/ |title=An Index to the work of Tom McCarthy |publisher=Surplus Matter |date=14 October 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/vintage/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780307278357&view=qa |title=Vintage / Anchor \" Knopf Doubleday \u2013 Vintage / Anchor |publisher=Randomhouse.com |date=25 March 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> In response [[Tom LeClair]] described him as a \"young and British [[Thomas Pynchon]].\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/books/review/men-in-space-tom-mccarthys-complex-novel.html | work=The New York Times | first=Stephen | last=Burn | title='Men in Space,' Tom McCarthy's Complex Novel | date=24 February 2012}}</ref> It was also shortlisted for the [[Walter Scott Prize]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Walter Scott historical fiction shortlist announced|publisher=BBC news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-12932522|accessdate=12 June 2011|date=1 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt has been described as \"unquestionably brilliant, usefully denting the model of the psychological realism that is the dominant mode of our conservative times by its unique, disorientating glance at modernism\" by Neel Mukherjee of [[The Times]] and \"an avant-garde epic, the first I can think of since Joyce's ''Ulysses''\" by Jonathan Dee of [[Harper's Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/gbx/mccarthy3.htm |title=C - Tom McCarthy |publisher=Complete-review.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\nLeo Robson in the [[New Statesman]] review describes the book as \"full of familiar delights and familiar tedium\", with \"Protracted descriptions of a pageant and a seance [that] drain the reader's will to live.\" It continues \"After a certain point, most sentences go something like this (not a parody): \"Everything seems connected: disparate locations twitch and burst into activity like limbs reacting to impulses sent from elsewhere in the body, booms and jibs obeying levers at the far end of a complex set of ropes and cogs and relays.\"\"<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/>\n\n===''Satin Island''===\n''[[Satin Island]]'' concerns a protagonist, U., who works for the Company. U. is employed as an anthropologist. The novel was released in 2015 and was shortlisted for the [[2015 Man Booker Prize]]<ref name=2015booker>{{cite web|title=Pulitzer winner makes Booker Prize shortlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34255672|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=19 October 2015|date=15 September 2015}}</ref> and the 2015 [[Goldsmiths Prize]].<ref name=2015goldsmiths>{{cite web|last1=Morgan|first1=Tom|title=Goldsmiths Prize shortlist 2015|url=http://www.gold.ac.uk/news/goldsmiths-prize-shortlist-2015/|website=Goldsmiths|accessdate=19 October 2015|date=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nIn a 2007 interview McCarthy claimed one of the main themes pervading his work to be that of repetition and duplication.<ref name=\"bookninja1\"/> The repetition in ''Remainder'' takes the form of re-enactments of events carried out by the wealthy post-traumatic hero in a process that some critics (such as Joyce Carol Oates in the ''[[New York Review of Books]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Joyce Carol Oates |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/20399 |title=Lest We Forget &#124; The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=19 July 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>) have seen as allegory for art itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shorttermmemoryloss.com/words/2005/11/about-accident-itself-i-can-say-very.html |title=short term memory loss ... a blog about books ...: About the accident itself I can say very little |publisher=Shorttermmemoryloss.com |date=14 November 2005 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> In ''Men in Space'' it takes the form of duplication of an artwork, and a set of patterns repeating over several centuries. In McCarthy's art projects it has taken the form of repeating sets of messages over radio in a homage to [[Jean Cocteau]]'s ''Orph\u00e9e''.<ref name=\"necronauts1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/caa.htm |title=The Necronautical Society - INS Events |publisher=Necronauts.org |date=2004-04-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> Boyd Tonkin, in his ''Independent'' profile on McCarthy, picks up on the notion that literature itself is a series of repetitions and duplications.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html |title=Tom McCarthy: How he became one of the brightest new prospects in British fiction \u2013 Features, Books |publisher=The Independent |date=21 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010 |location=London |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730122647/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html |archivedate=30 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt least one critic has connected McCarthy's work to \"failed transcendence\",<ref>{{cite news|author=Lee Rourke |url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/reviews/generalfiction/0,,2165228,00.html |title=Review: Men in Space by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Books.guardian.co.uk |date= 8 September 2007|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> and McCarthy has used the term failed transcendence in interviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jonathanderbyshire.typepad.com/blog/2007/09/men-in-space.html |title=Jonathan Derbyshire: Men in Space |publisher=Jonathanderbyshire.typepad.com |date=11 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrants.com/segundo/bss-155-tom-mccarthy-part-two/ |title=Tom McCarthy, Part Two (BSS #155) : The Bat Segundo Show |publisher=Edrants.com |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> to describe the collapse of the idealist project in philosophy, art and literature. Failed transcendence forms a central tenet of 'The New York Declaration on Inauthenticity', an INS talk delivered in the style of a propaganda statement by McCarthy and the philosopher Simon Critchley in 2007 in the [[Drawing Center]], New York.<ref name=\"canopycanopycanopy1\"/>\nIn a discussion with the artist Margarita Gluzberg, held in 2001 in London's [[Austrian Cultural Forum]], McCarthy cites [[Georges Bataille]]'s description of matter as \"that non-logical difference that represents in relation to the economy of the universe what crime represents in relation to the economy of the law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/interviews_margarita.htm |title=The Necronautical Society \u2013 INS interviews |publisher=Necronauts.org |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn a lecture delivered to the International James Joyce Symposium in 2004 in Dublin, McCarthy again cites Bataille, drawing on his notion of \"base materialism\" to throw light on the scatological sensibility displayed in Joyce's novels.<ref>{{cite web|author=Louis Armand |url=http://www.geocities.com/hypermedia_joyce/mccarthy.html |title=Hypermedia Joyce Studies: Darren Tofts |publisher=Oocities.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/hypermedia_joyce/mccarthy.html&date=2009-10-26+00:18:04|archivedate=26 October 2009}}</ref>\nThe detective in ''Men in Space'' is a radio surveillance operative who starts out boasting he \"can always get a strong signal\", but ends up losing the signal and then becoming deaf, cut off from all communication. In one interview, McCarthy discussed this character's similarity to [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s Harry Caul in ''[[The Conversation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.raincoast.com/index.php/weblog/in-conversation-with-tom-mccarthy-3 |title=Blog &#124; Raincoast Books |publisher=Blogs.raincoast.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcCarthy created an art project around [[Cocteau]]'s ''[[Orpheus (film)|Orph\u00e9e]]'', at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]] in London in 2004, which consisted of forty assistants cutting up text, projecting it onto the walls and then re-assembling it into cryptic messages which were transmitted around London and the world by radio and internet. This project was indebted to [[William S. Burroughs]]'s notions of viral media<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1971187.ece ''Times'' 23 June 2007 \"Publishing? It\u2019s an art form\"]</ref> and to [[Nicolas Abraham]] and [[Maria Torok]]'s notions of the \"crypt\", a space both of burial and encryption. The art-piece Black Box, originally displayed in Moderna Museet, Stockholm, in 2008, also involved constant radio transmissions. McCarthy has insisted that radio technology can be regarded as a metaphor for writing, comparing T.S. Eliot's \"The Waste Land\" to a radio programme.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Vandeputte |url=http://www.supplementmaterial.com/#8 |title=Radio, Archaeology, Literature: Tom Vandeputte in Conversation with Tom McCarthy |publisher=Perhaps (Perhaps) |date= |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 2008 [[Believer Book Award]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/200806/?read=believer_book_award |title=The Believer - The Believer Book Award |publisher=Believermag.com |date=2008-06-01 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> for ''Remainder''.\n* 2010 [[Man Booker Prize for Fiction]] (shortlist)\n* 2013 [[Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.yale.edu/2013/03/04/yale-awards-135-million-nine-writers |title=Yale awards $1.35 million to nine writers |work=YaleNews |author=Dorie Baker |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015 [[Man Booker Prize for Fiction]] (shortlist) <ref>https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/tom-mccarthy</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2018}}\n\n===Fiction===\n*''Navigation Was Always a Difficult Art'' (London: Vargas Organization, 2002), {{ISBN|0-9520274-5-3}}.\n*''Calling All Agents'' (London: Vargas Organization, 2003), {{ISBN|0-9520274-8-8}}.\n*''Remainder'' (Paris: Metronome Press, 2005), {{ISBN|2-916262-00-8}}; (London: Alma Books, 2006), {{ISBN|978-1-84688-041-4}}; (New York, NY: Vintage, 2007), {{ISBN|978-0-307-27835-7}}.\n*''Men in Space'' (London: Alma Books, 2007), {{ISBN|978-1-84688-033-9}}.\n*[[C (novel)|''C'']] (London: Vintage, 2010), {{ISBN|978-0-224-09020-9}}.\n*''Satin Island'' (New York: Knopf, 2015), {{ISBN|0-307-59395-9}}.\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'' (London: Granta, 2006), {{ISBN|978-1-86207-831-4}}; (Berkeley, CA: Counterpoint, 2008), {{ISBN|978-1-58243-405-6}}.\n* ''Transmission and the Individual Remix'': (Vintage, 2012) {{ISBN|978-0345803276}}\n*{{cite journal |author=McCarthy, Tom |authormask= |date=October 10, 2016 |title=Model behavior |department=Work for Hire |journal=The New Yorker |volume=92 |issue=32 |pages=72 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/10/10/the-best-if-worst-paid-job-i-ever-had |<!--accessdate=2018-02-09-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"The best, if worst-paid, job I ever had\".</ref>\n*''Typewriters, Bombs, Jellyfish: Essays'' (New York: New York Review Books, 2017), {{ISBN|978-1681370866}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.supplementmaterial.com/#mccarthy Radio, Archaeology, Literature: Tom Vandeputte in Conversation with Tom McCarthy]. Retrieved 2013-02-10\n* [http://www.untitledbooks.com/features/interviews/tom-mccarthy/ Interview, ''Untitled Books'']. Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/nov/24/tom-mccarthy-desktop# \"My desktop\"] in ''The Guardian''\n* [http://www.surplusmatter.com SurplusMatter.com McCarthy resource site]. Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://www.randomhouse.com/author/results.pperl?authorid=73469 Vintage, McCarthy's US publisher. Works detail.] Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://anthemmagazine.com/synecdoche-new-york/ Charlie Kaufman on Remainder and Synecdoche, NY]. Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://www.indigestmag.com/booklam6.htm A Review of ''Remainder''] from InDigest Magazine. Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://colinmarshall.libsyn.com/index.php?post_id=361846 Interview with McCarthy] on ''The Marketplace of Ideas'' (Audio, 35 mins). Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22083 Zadie Smith: \"Two Paths for the Novel\". Essay on ''Remainder''. 20 November 2008 ''The New York Review of Books'']. Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://dossierjournal.com/read/interviews/the-radical-ambiguity-of-tom-mccarthy/ Interview ''Dossier Journal''.] Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/books/audio/2010/sep/09/tom-mccarthy-c-booker-prize Reading from his novel ''C''] 9 September 2010 ''Guardian''. (Audio, 17 mis). Retrieved 2010-12-28\n* [http://bombmagazine.org/article/276933/tom-mccarthy 2015 ''Bomb Magazine'' interview of Tom McCarthy by Frederic Tuten]\n{{Believer Book Award |state=collapsed}}\n* Wrethed J. \u201cThe Phenomenology of Representation, Ritual, and the Sacred in Tom McCarthy\u2019s Remainder\u201d. Anthropoetics, XXIII, no. 1 Fall 2017. Available at: http://anthropoetics.ucla.edu/ap2301/2301wrethed/\n* Wrethed J. \u201c\u02bbWhere danger is, there rescue grows\u02bc: Technology, Time, and Dromology in Tom McCarthy\u2019s C\u201d. C21 Literature: journal of 21st-century writings, 5(3) 2017, p.&nbsp;3. DOI: http://doi.org/10.16995/c21.26\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCarthy, Tom}}\n[[Category:21st-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dulwich College]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Believer Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-distinguish|Men in Space|Man in Space|Men into Space|Manned spaceflight|Spaceman (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Lead too short|date=October 2015}}\n{{External links|date=October 2015}}}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Tom McCarthy\n| image =\n| imagesize = 60\n| caption = Tom McCarthy\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1969}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| occupation = Novelist, writer, artist\n| nationality = British\n| period = 2002\u2013present\n| genre =\n| subject =\n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'', ''Men in Space'', ''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'', [[C (novel)|''C'']], ''[[Satin Island]]''\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| website = {{url|http://vargas.org.uk/publications/ins/index.html}}\n}}\n'''Tom McCarthy''' (born 1969) is an English writer and artist. He has written four novels, his debut novel ''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'' published in 2005 by [[Metronome (artists' and writers' organ)|Metronome]] and his most recent published novel, ''[[Satin Island]]'', in 2015 by [[Alfred A. Knopf]].\n\n==Life and work==\nTom McCarthy was born in London in 1969 and lives in [[Central London]]. McCarthy grew up in [[Greenwich]], south London and was educated at [[Dulwich College]] (1978 to 1986) and later [[New College, Oxford]], where he studied English literature. He lived in Prague, where he worked as a nude model and in an American bar; Berlin, where he worked in an Irish pub; and Amsterdam, where he worked in a restaurant kitchen and reviewed books for the local edition of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine<ref name=\"thedaysofyore.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedaysofyore.com/tom-mccarthy/ |title=Tom McCarthy |publisher=The Days of Yore |date=2011-06-20 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> in the early 90s, before moving back to London. McCarthy's time in Prague forms the basis for his novel ''Men in Space''.<ref Name=\"Independent\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html \"Tom McCarthy: How he became one of the brightest new prospects in British fiction\" ''The Independent\" 21 September 2007]</ref> McCarthy has also worked as a television script editor, and co-edited ''[[Mute Magazine|Mute]]'' magazine. Prior to his success he lived and wrote in a tower block flat on the [[Golden Lane Estate]] beside [[Barbican Estate|the Barbican]].<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\n===Writing and publishing===\nMcCarthy's debut novel ''Remainder'' was written in 2001<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\">{{cite web|last=Robson |first=Leo |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2010/08/mccarthy-novel-serge-smith |title=C |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=2010-08-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> and rejected by mainstream UK publishers. It was published in November 2005 by the small Paris-based art publisher [[Metronome Press]] and distributed through gallery and museum shops, but not in chain bookstores<ref Name=\"Independent\"/> and then received widespread critical attention in the literary and mainstream press, with one of its first reviews, in December 2005, on ReadySteadyBook who called it \"one of the most important novels written in a long, long time.\" The ''London Review of Books'' called it \"a very good novel indeed\" and ''The Independent'' claimed that \"its minatory brilliance calls for classic status\".<ref>{{cite web|author=the complete review \u2013 all rights reserved |url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/gbx/mccarthy.htm |title=Remainder \u2013 Tom McCarthy |publisher=Complete-review.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> The novel was re-published by the independent publisher [[Alma Books]] in the UK (2006), and the [[Bertelsmann]] subsidiary [[Vintage Books|Vintage]] in the US (2007), where it ranked as an Amazon top one-hundred seller and entered the ''Los Angeles Times'' Bestseller list.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} On its American publication the ''New York Times'' dedicated the front cover of its book section to the novel, calling the book \"a work of novelistic philosophy, as disturbing as it is funny\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/25/books/review/Schillinger.t.html | work=The New York Times | title=Play It Again | first=Liesl | last=Schillinger | date=25 February 2007}}</ref> In 2008 ''Remainder'' won the fourth annual [[Believer Book Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/200806/?read=believer_book_award |title=The Believer \u2013 The Believer Book Award |publisher=Believermag.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Zadie Smith wrote in the ''New York Review of Books'' that it was \"one of the great English novels of the last ten years\", suggesting it showed a future path that the novel \"might, with difficulty, follow\".<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Zadie Smith |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22083 |title=Two Paths for the Novel &#124; The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=20 November 2008 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> It has since been translated into fourteen languages, and a film adaptation directed by [[Omer Fast]] was released in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/novel-idea/ |title=Frieze Magazine &#124; Archive &#124; Novel Idea |publisher=Frieze.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1847672/|title=Remainder (2015)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref>Editions have been published, or are scheduled to be published, in Chinese (Shanghai Translation Publishing House and Ten Points Publishing House), Croatian ([http://oceanmore.hr/knjiga.php?id_knjiga=47 Oceanmore]), Dutch ([http://uitgeverijprometheus.nl/index.php?option=com_pac&view=boek_detail&isbn=9789044614152&Itemid=6 Prometheus]), French (Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures and [http://www.jailu.com/albums_detail.cfm?id=34922 J\u2019ai Lu]), German ([http://www.diaphanes.de/scripts/buch.php?ID=172 Diaphanes]), Greek (Papyros Publishing Group), Hebrew (Achuzat Bayit), Italian ([http://isbnedizioni.it/catalogo/narrativa/deja-vu/ ISBN Edizioni]), Japanese (Shinchosha Publishing Company), Korean (Minumsa), Portuguese ([http://www.estampa.pt/novosite/index.php?t=detalhe&id=1792 Editorial Estampa]), Russian ([http://admarginem.ru/books/1884/ Ad Marginem]), Spanish ([http://www.lenguadetrapo.com/libro.php?sec=OL&item=229 Lengua de Trapo]) and Turkish (Encore Yay\u0131nlar\u0131).</ref> Several big publishing houses who had rejected the novel returned to him with enthusiastic offers, which McCarthy rejected, commenting that \"it's the same book as it was two years ago.\"<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\n{{anchor|Tintin and the Secret of Literature}}\nA work of literary criticism by McCarthy, ''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'', was released by [[Granta Books]] in June 2006, with French (Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures), Spanish (El Tercer Nombre), Italian (Piemme) and American editions (Counterpoint) following in 2007-8.<ref>Tom McCarthy, ''Tintin e il segreto della letteratura'' (Milan: Piemme, 2007). {{ISBN|978-88-384-8668-5}}; ''Tintin et le secret de la litt\u00e9rature'' (Paris: Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures, 2006). {{ISBN|978-2-01-237258-0}}; ''Tint\u00edn y el secreto de la literatura'' (Madrid: El Tercer Nombre, 2007). {{ISBN|978-84-96693-11-1}}</ref> The book attempted a reading of Herg\u00e9's ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' books through the prism of structuralist and post-structuralist literary theory. It divided reviewers, with some critics disliking the book's references to [[Jacques Derrida]] and [[Roland Barthes]]. Killian Fox in ''The Observer'' praised \"its author's obsessive approach, his breathtaking grasp of the oeuvre and the sheer exuberance with which he tackles his subject\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Killian Fox |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jul/16/booksforchildrenandteenagers.features |title=Observer review: Tintin and the Secret of Literature by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Guardian |date= 16 July 2006|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> However, in ''The Guardian'', Kathryn Hughes criticised its methodology and style: \"McCarthy's text has that pleased-with-itself smirk that was so characteristic of the early 90s, when journalists started purloining critical theory from the academy, liking the way it made them feel clever\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Kathryn Hughes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jul/15/highereducation.news |title=Review: Tintin and the Secret of Literature by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books |publisher=The Guardian |date= 14 July 2006|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> McCarthy commented: \"Granta asked if I wanted to write a book on Freud or Derrida or someone like that, and I said: 'Well, if I write about Herg\u00e9 I can write about Freud, Derrida and whole bunch of other people, plus it'll be much more fun.' It was received well for the most part. There were one or two hilarious English reviews in which you could virtually see the reviewer's veins bursting with little-England rage at the book's continental bent.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viewfromheremagazine.com/2008/03/mike-interviews-tom-mccarthy.html |title=The view from here literary magazine: Mike Interviews: Tom McCarthy Part 1 of 3 |publisher=Viewfromheremagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Alma Books published his second novel, ''Men in Space'', much of which was written prior to ''Remainder''. It has since been published in many languages including Greek and French.<ref>Tom McCarthy, ''Men in space'' (''\u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1'') (Athens: Papyros, 2008). {{ISBN|978-960-6715-60-0}}; ''Les Cosmonautes au paradis'' (Paris: Hachette Litt\u00e9ratures, 2009). {{ISBN|978-2-01-237406-5}}</ref> McCarthy has also published numerous stories, essays and articles on literature, philosophy and art in publications including ''The Observer'', ''The Times Literary Supplement'', ''The London Review of Books'', ''Artforum'' and ''The New York Times'', as well as in anthologies such as ''London from Punk to Blair'' (Reaktion Books), ''Theology and the Political'' (Duke University Press), ''The Milgram Reenactment'' (Jan van Eyck Press) and ''The Empty Page: Fiction Inspired by Sonic Youth'' (Serpent's Tail).\n\nIn 2004 he published an essay on excrement in the work of James Joyce in the online literary journal ''Hypermedia Joyce Studies''. In 2008 an essay by McCarthy on Alain Robbe-Grillet, an author he has often expressed an admiration for, was published in the new Oneworld Classics English edition of Robbe-Grillet's ''Jealousy''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/may/08/top10s.modernists |title=Tom McCarthy's top 10 European modernists &#124; Books &#124; guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian |date= 22 July 2008|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In February 2015 McCarthy published a new novel titled ''Satin Island'' which was shortlisted for that year's [[Man Booker Prize]]; when he began it, he said, \"It's going to have a leitmotif of a parachutist falling to earth, having realised that his parachute has been sabotaged: his relation to the landscape, death, technology.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Johncock|first=Ben|title=Tom McCarthy: My desktop|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2011/nov/24/tom-mccarthy-desktop|accessdate=17 June 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=24 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===McCarthy's International Necronautical Society (INS) and Art===\nSince 1999 McCarthy has been 'general secretary' of a 'semi-fictitious organisation' he co-founded with his friend<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblioklept.org/tag/simon-critchley/ |title=Simon Critchley |publisher=Biblioklept |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> the philosopher [[Simon Critchley]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookprizes/8058014/Man-Booker-Prize-the-shortlist.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Man Booker Prize: the shortlist | date=12 October 2010}}</ref> called the International Necronautical Society (INS) \"devoted to mind-bending projects that would do for death what the Surrealists had done for sex\".<ref Name=\"Independent\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/fictionreviews/3667868/Lost-in-the-orbits-of-spies-and-mobsters.html |title=Lost in the orbits of spies and mobsters |publisher=Telegraph |date=13 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Having failed to interest publishers in his novels in 2001-2, he made art projects under the INS name.<ref name=\"thewhitereview.org\">{{cite web|author=Interview with Tom McCarthy |url=http://www.thewhitereview.org/interviews/interview-with-tom-mccarthy-2/ |title=Interview with Tom McCarthy |publisher=The White Review |date=2014-10-31 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref><ref name=\"readysteadybook.com\">{{cite web|author=Anne Sherwood Pundyk |url=http://www.readysteadybook.com/Article.aspx?page=tommccarthy |title=Tom McCarthy \u00ab Interview \u00ab ReadySteadyBook - for literature |publisher=Readysteadybook.com |date=2009-07-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> McCarthy handed out his International Necronautical Society or INS manifestos at a mock art fair organised by artist [[Gavin Turk]].<ref name=\"readysteadybook.com\"/> The INS operates through publications, live events, media interventions and more conventional art exhibitions.\n\nIn a 2007 interview with the website Bookninja, McCarthy explained the circumstances that led to the formation of the INS: \"I was quite well integrated into the art world in London by the late nineties, and on top of that I\u2019d for some time had an interest in the modes and procedures of early twentieth century avant-gardes like the Futurists and Surrealists: their semi-corporate, semi-political structures of committees and subcommittees, their use of manifestos, proclamations and denunciations\".<ref name=\"bookninja1\">{{cite web|url=http://bookninja.com/magazine/fall2007/mccarthy.htm |title=In The Magazine |publisher=Bookninja |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nDespite his initial claim that the INS was 'not an art project',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://surplusmatter.com/interviews/interviews-with/its-impossible-to-think-of-writing-without-thinking-of-death-tom-mccarthy-on-the-necronautical-society/ |title=An Index to the work of Tom McCarthy |publisher=Surplus Matter |date=1 February 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> McCarthy has accepted invitations to show work in his capacity as INS general secretary at art institutions around the world, including Tate Britain and the Institute of Contemporary Art in London, Moderna Museet Stockholm, the Drawing Center New York, Kunstwerke Berlin, Hartware MedienKunstVerein Dortmund, and Substation Gallery Singapore.<ref Name=\"Independent\"/>\n\nThe INS has been described by ''Art Monthly'' as \"a group of wayward literati and sweet-talking parodists\",<ref name=\"necronauts1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/art_monthly_04.htm |title=The Necronautical Society \u2013 INS in the Press |publisher=Necronauts.org |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> and as \"obscure\" by ''[[The Australian]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/tintin-and-the-secret-of-literature/story-e6frg8no-1111112339055 | first=Alistair | last=Jones | title=Tintin and the Secret of Literature | date=14 October 2006 | work=The Australian}}</ref> In 2003 the INS hacked the [[BBC]] website and inserted propaganda into its source code. The following year, they set up a broadcasting unit at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]] from which more than forty assistants generated non-stop \"poem-codes\" which were transmitted over FM radio in London and by internet to collaborating radio stations around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almabooks.com/page.html?id=17 |title=Overture Publishing |publisher=Alma Books |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> In 2008 a more mechanical version of this piece was displayed at Stockholm's Moderna Museet, in which an aeroplane Black Box transmitter sent out a stream of similar messages.<ref>{{cite web|author=mikejfrench |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cm4379AkUb0 |title=Tom McCarthy om Black Box |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, after McCarthy and INS Chief Philosopher [[Simon Critchley]] had delivered the 'INS Declaration on Inauthenticity' at New York's Drawing Center, the critic Peter Schwenger alleged in ''[[Triple Canopy (online magazine)|Triple Canopy]]'' that the two men who appeared in the gallery were not in fact Critchley and McCarthy.<ref name=\"canopycanopycanopy1\">{{cite web|url=http://canopycanopycanopy.com/1/state_of_inauthenticity |title=The State of Inauthenticity \u2013 Triple Canopy |publisher=Canopycanopycanopy.com |date=25 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Taking his claim as an inspiration, McCarthy and Critchley did indeed replace themselves with actors when delivering the Declaration one year later at Tate Britain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/context-comment/video/tate-triennial-2009-prologue-4-borders-simon-critchley-and-tom-mccarthy-tate |title=Tate Channel: Tate Triennial 2009 Prologue 4: Borders |publisher=Tate |date= |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> When invited to deliver the Declaration a third time at the 2009 Athens Biennial, they announced that the Declaration would henceforth be outsourced to any institution who wanted it, and commissioned a Greek translation, which was subsequently delivered by Greek actors in Athens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.athensbiennial.org/AB2PressReleases&PreviewScheduleENGLISH.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725022238/http://www.athensbiennial.org/AB2PressReleases%26PreviewScheduleENGLISH.pdf |archivedate=25 July 2011 |title=2nd Athens Biennale 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMcCarthy has made independent artworks. In 2005 he exhibited, at The Western Front Gallery, Vancouver, the multimedia installation piece 'Greenwich Degree Zero', produced in collaboration with artist [[Rod Dickinson]], which (in a tribute to [[Joseph Conrad]]'s 1907 novel ''The Secret Agent''), depicted the Greenwich Observatory burning the ground. The piece was subsequently purchased by the Arts Council England's permanent collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/collections/arts-council-collection/greenwich-degree-zero-2005-6/ |title=Greenwich Degree Zero, 2005-6 |publisher=Arts Council |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 he collaborated with French artist Loris Gr\u00e9aud to produce an 'Ontic Helpline' for a fictitious 'Thanatalogical Corporation' \u2013 a black telephone that transfers callers through an endless loop of pre-recorded messages. The telephone was displayed in the FiAC collection in Paris, and purchased by gallerists/collectors Solene Guillier and Nathalie Boutin. McCarthy wrote the script for Johan Grimonprez's feature film ''Double Take'' (2009). The script consists of a short story, loosely based on Borges's '25 August 1983', in which Hitchcock meets his double on the set of one of his films.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1386926/ |title=Double Take (2009)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> The film won the Black Pearl award (MEIFF, Abu Dhabi) in 2009. McCarthy has also tutored and lectured at various institutions including the [[Architectural Association]], [[Central Saint Martins School of Art]], the [[Royal College of Art]], [[London Consortium]] and [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Novels==\n===''Remainder''===\n''[[Remainder (novel)|Remainder]]'' tells the story of an unnamed hero traumatised by an accident which \"involved something falling from the sky\". Eight and a half million pounds richer due to a compensation settlement but hopelessly estranged from the world around him, ''Remainder'''s protagonist spends his time and money obsessively reconstructing and re-enacting vaguely remembered scenes and situations from his past, such as a large building with piano music in the distance, the familiar smells and sounds of liver frying and spluttering, or lethargic cats lounging on roofs until they tumble off them. These re-enactments are driven by a need to inhabit the world \"authentically\" rather than in the \"second-hand\" manner that his traumatic situation has bequeathed him. When the recreation of mundane events fails to quench this thirst for authenticity, he starts re-enacting more and more violent events.\n\n===''Men in Space''===\nSet in a Central Europe rapidly fragmenting after the fall of Communism, ''Men in Space'' follows a cast of dissolute Bohemians, political refugees, football referees, deaf police agents, assassins and stranded astronauts as they chase a stolen icon painting from Sofia to Prague and beyond. The icon's melancholy orbit is reflected in the various characters' ellipses and near-misses as they career vertiginously through all kinds of space, be it physical, political, emotional or metaphysical. McCarthy uses these settings to present a vision of humanity adrift in history, and a world in a state of disintegration.\n\n===''C''===\nOpening in England at the turn of the twentieth century, ''C'' is the story of a boy named Serge Carrefax, whose father spends his time experimenting with wireless communication while running a school for deaf children. Serge grows up amid the noise and silence with his brilliant but troubled older sister, Sophie: an intense sibling relationship that stays with him as he heads off into an equally troubled larger world. After a fling with a nurse at a Bohemian spa, Serge serves in World War I as a radio operator for reconnaissance planes. When his plane is shot down, Serge is taken to a German prison camp, from which he escapes. Back in London, he's recruited for a mission to Cairo on behalf of the shadowy Empire Wireless Chain.\n\nMcCarthy's novel ''C'' was released in late 2010, in the US with Knopf, in the UK with Jonathan Cape. It divided critics.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/booknews/7913342/Peter-Carey-could-be-three-time-Booker-winner.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Stephen | last=Adams | title=Peter Carey could be three-time Booker winner | date=27 July 2010}}</ref>\nMcCarthy has described this novel in previous interviews as dealing with technology and mourning. The book was shortlisted for the 2010 [[Man Booker Prize]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://surplusmatter.com/interviews/interviews-with/watch-that-space-or-literatures-proper-territory/ |title=An Index to the work of Tom McCarthy |publisher=Surplus Matter |date=14 October 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/vintage/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780307278357&view=qa |title=Vintage / Anchor \" Knopf Doubleday \u2013 Vintage / Anchor |publisher=Randomhouse.com |date=25 March 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> In response [[Tom LeClair]] described him as a \"young and British [[Thomas Pynchon]].\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/26/books/review/men-in-space-tom-mccarthys-complex-novel.html | work=The New York Times | first=Stephen | last=Burn | title='Men in Space,' Tom McCarthy's Complex Novel | date=24 February 2012}}</ref> It was also shortlisted for the [[Walter Scott Prize]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Walter Scott historical fiction shortlist announced|publisher=BBC news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-south-scotland-12932522|accessdate=12 June 2011|date=1 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt has been described as \"unquestionably brilliant, usefully denting the model of the psychological realism that is the dominant mode of our conservative times by its unique, disorientating glance at modernism\" by Neel Mukherjee of [[The Times]] and \"an avant-garde epic, the first I can think of since Joyce's ''Ulysses''\" by Jonathan Dee of [[Harper's Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.complete-review.com/reviews/gbx/mccarthy3.htm |title=C - Tom McCarthy |publisher=Complete-review.com |date= |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref>\n\nLeo Robson in the [[New Statesman]] review describes the book as \"full of familiar delights and familiar tedium\", with \"Protracted descriptions of a pageant and a seance [that] drain the reader's will to live.\" It continues \"After a certain point, most sentences go something like this (not a parody): \"Everything seems connected: disparate locations twitch and burst into activity like limbs reacting to impulses sent from elsewhere in the body, booms and jibs obeying levers at the far end of a complex set of ropes and cogs and relays.\"\"<ref name=\"newstatesman.com\"/>\n\n===''Satin Island''===\n''[[Satin Island]]'' concerns a protagonist, U., who works for the Company. U. is employed as an anthropologist. The novel was released in 2015 and was shortlisted for the [[2015 Man Booker Prize]]<ref name=2015booker>{{cite web|title=Pulitzer winner makes Booker Prize shortlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34255672|website=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=19 October 2015|date=15 September 2015}}</ref> and the 2015 [[Goldsmiths Prize]].<ref name=2015goldsmiths>{{cite web|last1=Morgan|first1=Tom|title=Goldsmiths Prize shortlist 2015|url=http://www.gold.ac.uk/news/goldsmiths-prize-shortlist-2015/|website=Goldsmiths|accessdate=19 October 2015|date=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nIn a 2007 interview McCarthy claimed one of the main themes pervading his work to be that of repetition and duplication.<ref name=\"bookninja1\"/> The repetition in ''Remainder'' takes the form of re-enactments of events carried out by the wealthy post-traumatic hero in a process that some critics (such as Joyce Carol Oates in the ''[[New York Review of Books]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Joyce Carol Oates |url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/20399 |title=Lest We Forget &#124; The New York Review of Books |publisher=Nybooks.com |date=19 July 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>) have seen as allegory for art itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shorttermmemoryloss.com/words/2005/11/about-accident-itself-i-can-say-very.html |title=short term memory loss ... a blog about books ...: About the accident itself I can say very little |publisher=Shorttermmemoryloss.com |date=14 November 2005 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> In ''Men in Space'' it takes the form of duplication of an artwork, and a set of patterns repeating over several centuries. In McCarthy's art projects it has taken the form of repeating sets of messages over radio in a homage to [[Jean Cocteau]]'s ''Orph\u00e9e''.<ref name=\"necronauts1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/caa.htm |title=The Necronautical Society - INS Events |publisher=Necronauts.org |date=2004-04-13 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> Boyd Tonkin, in his ''Independent'' profile on McCarthy, picks up on the notion that literature itself is a series of repetitions and duplications.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html |title=Tom McCarthy: How he became one of the brightest new prospects in British fiction \u2013 Features, Books |publisher=The Independent |date=21 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010 |location=London |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730122647/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/tom-mccarthy-how-he-became-one-of-the-brightest-new-prospects-in-british-fiction-464502.html |archivedate=30 July 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt least one critic has connected McCarthy's work to \"failed transcendence\",<ref>{{cite news|author=Lee Rourke |url=http://books.guardian.co.uk/reviews/generalfiction/0,,2165228,00.html |title=Review: Men in Space by Tom McCarthy &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Books.guardian.co.uk |date= 8 September 2007|accessdate=15 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> and McCarthy has used the term failed transcendence in interviews<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jonathanderbyshire.typepad.com/blog/2007/09/men-in-space.html |title=Jonathan Derbyshire: Men in Space |publisher=Jonathanderbyshire.typepad.com |date=11 September 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrants.com/segundo/bss-155-tom-mccarthy-part-two/ |title=Tom McCarthy, Part Two (BSS #155) : The Bat Segundo Show |publisher=Edrants.com |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> to describe the collapse of the idealist project in philosophy, art and literature. Failed transcendence forms a central tenet of 'The New York Declaration on Inauthenticity', an INS talk delivered in the style of a propaganda statement by McCarthy and the philosopher Simon Critchley in 2007 in the [[Drawing Center]], New York.<ref name=\"canopycanopycanopy1\"/>\nIn a discussion with the artist Margarita Gluzberg, held in 2001 in London's [[Austrian Cultural Forum]], McCarthy cites [[Georges Bataille]]'s description of matter as \"that non-logical difference that represents in relation to the economy of the universe what crime represents in relation to the economy of the law\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.necronauts.org/interviews_margarita.htm |title=The Necronautical Society \u2013 INS interviews |publisher=Necronauts.org |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn a lecture delivered to the International James Joyce Symposium in 2004 in Dublin, McCarthy again cites Bataille, drawing on his notion of \"base materialism\" to throw light on the scatological sensibility displayed in Joyce's novels.<ref>{{cite web|author=Louis Armand |url=http://www.geocities.com/hypermedia_joyce/mccarthy.html |title=Hypermedia Joyce Studies: Darren Tofts |publisher=Oocities.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/hypermedia_joyce/mccarthy.html&date=2009-10-26+00:18:04|archivedate=26 October 2009}}</ref>\nThe detective in ''Men in Space'' is a radio surveillance operative who starts out boasting he \"can always get a strong signal\", but ends up losing the signal and then becoming deaf, cut off from all communication. In one interview, McCarthy discussed this character's similarity to [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s Harry Caul in ''[[The Conversation]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.raincoast.com/index.php/weblog/in-conversation-with-tom-mccarthy-3 |title=Blog &#124; Raincoast Books |publisher=Blogs.raincoast.com |date= |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcCarthy created an art project around [[Cocteau]]'s ''[[Orpheus (film)|Orph\u00e9e]]'', at the [[Institute of Contemporary Arts]] in London in 2004, which consisted of forty assistants cutting up text, projecting it onto the walls and then re-assembling it into cryptic messages which were transmitted around London and the world by radio and internet. This project was indebted to [[William S. Burroughs]]'s notions of viral media<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article1971187.ece ''Times'' 23 June 2007 \"Publishing? It\u2019s an art form\"]</ref> and to [[Nicolas Abraham]] and [[Maria Torok]]'s notions of the \"crypt\", a space both of burial and encryption. The art-piece Black Box, originally displayed in Moderna Museet, Stockholm, in 2008, also involved constant radio transmissions. McCarthy has insisted that radio technology can be regarded as a metaphor for writing, comparing T.S. Eliot's \"The Waste Land\" to a radio programme.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Vandeputte |url=http://www.supplementmaterial.com/#8 |title=Radio, Archaeology, Literature: Tom Vandeputte in Conversation with Tom McCarthy |publisher=Perhaps (Perhaps) |date= |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* 2008 [[Believer Book Award]]<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.believermag.com/issues/200806/?read=believer_book_award |title=The Believer - The Believer Book Award |publisher=Believermag.com |date=2008-06-01 |accessdate=2015-10-07}}</ref> for ''Remainder''.\n* 2010 [[Man Booker Prize for Fiction]] (shortlist)\n* 2013 [[Windham\u2013Campbell Literature Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.yale.edu/2013/03/04/yale-awards-135-million-nine-writers |title=Yale awards $1.35 million to nine writers |work=YaleNews |author=Dorie Baker |date=4 March 2013 |accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n* 2015 [[Man Booker Prize for Fiction]] (shortlist) <ref>https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/tom-mccarthy</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2018}}\n\n===Fiction===\n*''Navigation Was Always a Difficult Art'' (London: Vargas Organization, 2002), {{ISBN|0-9520274-5-3}}.\n*''Calling All Agents'' (London: Vargas Organization, 2003), {{ISBN|0-9520274-8-8}}.\n*''Remainder'' (Paris: Metronome Press, 2005), {{ISBN|2-916262-00-8}}; (London: Alma Books, 2006), {{ISBN|978-1-84688-041-4}}; (New York, NY: Vintage, 2007), {{ISBN|978-0-307-27835-7}}.\n*''Men in Space'' (London: Alma Books, 2007), {{ISBN|978-1-84688-033-9}}.\n*[[C (novel)|''C'']] (London: Vintage, 2010), {{ISBN|978-0-224-09020-9}}.\n*''Satin Island'' (New York: Knopf, 2015), {{ISBN|0-307-59395-9}}.\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Tintin and the Secret of Literature'' (London: Granta, 2006), {{ISBN|978-1-86207-831-4}}; (Berkeley, CA: Counterpoint, 2008), {{ISBN|978-1-58243-405-6}}.\n* ''Transmission and the Individual Remix'': (Vintage, 2012) {{ISBN|978-0345803276}}\n*{{cite journal |author=McCarthy, Tom |authormask= |date=October 10, 2016 |title=Model behavior |department=Work for Hire |journal=The New Yorker |volume=92 |issue=32 |pages=72 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/10/10/the-best-if-worst-paid-job-i-ever-had |<!--accessdate=2018-02-09-->}}<ref>Online version is titled \"The best, if worst-paid, job I ever had\".</ref>\n*''Typewriters, Bombs, Jellyfish: Essays'' (New York: New York Review Books, 2017), {{ISBN|978-1681370866}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiqu